revision.text:
The '''infrared Ca II triplet''', commonly known as the '''Calcium triplet''', is a triplet of three [[ionised]] [[calcium]] [[spectral lines]] at the [[wavelength]] of 8498&nbsp;[[Ångstrom|Å]], 8542&nbsp;Å and 8662&nbsp;Å. The triplet has a strong emission,<ref> {{cite web |author=Polidan, R. S. |title=On the Detection of Binary be Stars |date=1976 |url=http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?1976IAUS...70..401P&defaultprint=YES&filetype=.pdf |journal=Be and Shell Stars: IAU Symposium no. 70 |page=405 }}</ref> and is most prominently observed in the [[Absorption spectroscopy|absorption]] of [[spectral type]] [[G-type main-sequence star|G]], [[K-type main-sequence star|K]] and [[Stellar classification#Class M|M]] stars.<ref>{{cite web |last = Andretta |last2 = Busà |last3=Gomez |last4= Terranegra |date=2005 |url =http://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/pdf/2005/05/aa1745.pdf |title =The Ca II Infrared Triplet as a stellar activity diagnostic |publisher =Astronomy & Astrophysics |page=669 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author = Jonathan Tennyson |title = Astronomical Spectroscopy. An introduction to the atomic and molecular physics in astronomical spectra |url = http://www.ursusmajor.ch/downloads/analysis-and-interpretation-of-astronomical-sp.pdf |date = 2005 |publisher = [[Imperial College Press]] |page = 94 |access-date = 2016-07-09 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160116131018/http://www.ursusmajor.ch/downloads/analysis-and-interpretation-of-astronomical-sp.pdf# |archive-date = 2016-01-16 |dead-url = yes |df = }}</ref>
==See also== *[[Fraunhofer lines]] *[[Infrared spectroscopy]]
