'''Euboea''' (/juːˈbiːə/; [[Ancient Greek]]: Ευβοια) was the name of several women in [[Greek mythology]].
*Euboea, one of the daughters of the river-god [[Asterion (god)|Asterion]]. She and her sisters, [[Acraea]] and [[Prosymna (mythology)|Prosymna]], were the nurses of [[Hera]].<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], ''Description of Greece'', 2. 17. 1</ref><ref>[http://www.theoi.com/Nymphe/NymphaiAsterionides.html Theoi Project - Nymphai Asterionides]</ref> *Euboea, a [[Naiad]], daughter of the [[Boeotia]]n river-god [[Asopus]] and of [[Metope (mythology)|Metope]].<ref>[[Diodorus Siculus]], ''Library of History'', 4. 72. 1</ref> [[Poseidon]] abducted her.<ref>[[Corinna]], Fragment 654 (trans. Campbell)</ref> The island of [[Euboea]] was given her name.<ref>[[Eustathius of Thessalonica|Eustathius]] on [[Homer]], p. 278</ref><ref>[[Nonnus]], ''[[Dionysiaca]]'' 42. 411</ref><ref>[http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/1168.html William Smith, ''Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology'', v. 2, page 60]</ref><ref>[http://www.theoi.com/Nymphe/NympheEuboia.html Theoi Project - Nymphe Euboia]</ref> *Euboea, daughter of Larymnus. She and [[Polybus of Sicyon]] were possible parents of [[Glaucus]].<ref>[[Athenaeus]], ''Banquet of the Learned'', 7. 296b (p. 329)</ref> *Euboea, daughter of Macareus, king of [[Locris]]. She bore [[Apollo]] a son, [[Agreus]].<ref>[[Hyginus]], ''Fabulae'', 161</ref><ref>[http://www.theoi.com/Olympios/ApollonFamily.html Theoi Project - Apollon Family]</ref> *Euboea, one of the fifty daughters of [[Thespius]] and Megamede. She bore [[Heracles]] a son Olympus.<ref>[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]]. ''The Library'', [http://www.theoi.com/Text/Apollodorus2.html 2.7.8.].</ref> *Euboea, a [[hero]]ine and [[eponym]] of the island of [[Euboea]].<ref>[[Strabo]], ''Geography'' 10. 1. 3</ref><ref>[[Stephanus of Byzantium]] s. v. ''Euboia''</ref> May be identical with one of the above. *Euboea, mother of [[Triopas]] by [[Phorbas (king of Argos)|Phorbas]].<ref>Schol. ''ad Eurip. Or.'' 920</ref>
