This is a '''list of the wettest tropical cyclones''', listing all [[tropical cyclones]] known to have dropped at least {{Convert|1270|mm|in}} of precipitation on a single location. Data is most complete for Australia, Cuba, Dominican Republic, Japan, Hong Kong, Mexico, Yap, Chuuk, and the United States, with fragmentary data available for other countries. The [[Overseas department|French region]] of [[Réunion]] holds several world records for tropical cyclone and worldwide rainfall due to rough topography of the island and its proximity to the Indian Ocean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imd.gov.in/doc/988_en-2.final.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413131352/http://www.imd.gov.in/doc/988_en-2.final.pdf |archivedate=2014-04-13 |df= }}</ref>
== Overall Wettest == [[File:Commer.jpg|thumb|right|[[Commerson Crater]] in [[Réunion]], [[France]] has received over 5.5 metres of rain from tropical cyclones on at least two separate occasions.]]{{Wettest tropical cyclones on Earth|align=left}} [[File:Typhoon Morakot Aug 7 2009.jpg|thumb|right|[[Typhoon Morakot]] approaching Taiwan on August 7, 2009. Due to its rugged topography, Taiwan sees extreme rain from tropical cyclones, particularly in its central mountain range.]] [[File:Kihotown Sehara Miepref No,3.jpg|thumb|right|The heavy rains from [[Tropical Storm Talas (2011)|Tropical Storm Talas]] triggered numerous landslides, such as this one in [[Kihō, Mie|Kihō]], across the mountainous terrain of Japan.]] [[File:Support during Hurricane Harvey (TX) (50).jpg|thumb|Flooding in Texas on August 31, 2017 from [[Hurricane Harvey]]. Harvey stalled over the state of Texas for two days due to high pressure ridges on both sides, resulting in massive flooding.]]
